<span class="small_author">21 May 15 | Kaija Straumanis | </span>
<span class="comments_invite"> <a class="comments_invite" href="http://www.rochester.edu/College/translation/threepercent/index.php?id=14582#disqus_thread">Comments</a>


<div class="blog_body clearfix">

	<p>The <a href="http://www.rochester.edu/College/translation/threepercent/index.php?id=14572">latest addition</a> to our <a href="http://www.rochester.edu/College/translation/threepercent/index.php?s=reviews">Reviews</a> section is a piece by Vincent Francone on Milo≈° Djurdjeviƒá&#8217;s <em>Morse, My Deaf Friend</em>, translated by the author and published by Ugly Duckling Presse.</p>

	<p>The chapbook itself is short‚Äîclocking in at 32 pages‚Äîand is yet another beautiful work of print done by Ugly Duckling. Here&#8217;s the beginning of Vince&#8217;s review, which tries to get a grasp on what to expect, or not to expect, from poems labeled as &#8220;avant-garde&#8221;:</p>

	<blockquote>
		<p>There‚Äôs little to say about a series of prose poems that willfully refuse to identify pronoun antecedents. Or perhaps there are a million things. The poems in _Morse, My Deaf Friend_‚Äî the chapbook by Milo≈° Djurdjeviƒá published by Ugly Duckling Presse as part of their Eastern European Poets Series‚Äî will be confounding to those accustomed to poetry that holds its reader‚Äôs hand. These poems do not. They are elliptical and strange and offer very few concrete signifiers.</p>
	</blockquote>

	<p>For the rest of the review, go <a href="http://www.rochester.edu/College/translation/threepercent/index.php?id=14572">here.</a></p>


